/u/nomnaut on Astronomers have detected traces of methyl chloride, or Freon-40, surrounding infant stars and the comet 67P/Churyumov-Gerasimenko, suggesting it forms naturally in interstellar clouds. The findings quash the hope that some researchers had that the compound might signal the presence of life.
But the most specific condition for the evolution of life is stability. Sure, there were extinction events on earth, but earth as a planet was still around. I can’t imagine how hectic and volatile the beginning of the universe was, let alone there being enough time for life to develop and evolve. I agree that we shouldn’t be the first, but it would appear that we are. Or maybe, we are (one of) the last, and there was a time when life flourished in the universe but now it has grown too cold, dark and distant.   